node.text:
We’re so excited to announce Noma Projects and the launch of Project 001, noma’s line of garums, coming later this year. This is the culmination of 18 years of knowledge, craft and experimentation channeled into a new endeavor. To bring Project 001 to life, we collaborated with design agency @gretelnyc and one of our long-time favorite artists, @davidshrigley . For first access to preorders and news on upcoming projects, visit the link in bio! 

Music: @stefanpasborg / Ibrahim Electric
DOP: Mathias Nyholm Schmidt 
Editor: Rasmus Nyholm Schmidt

A small ingredient with a big story…

Last week our kitchen manager visited a very unique place to select fruits for one of the dishes on our summer menu.

These currants are from the @pometet.ku , operated by Copenhagen University as part of the Nordic Gene Bank. Pomology is the scientific study and cultivation of fruits, and the fruits and nuts at the Pometet are specifically grown for research and teaching purposes, which most importantly, includes maintaining the seeds of every variety grown. 

Currently this collection, or pomet, consists of nearly 750 apple varieties and 80 - 120 different fruit varieties, and what you see here is about 10 different currant varieties.

node.text: Happiest of birthdays to the greatest man in the universe, our very own Ali Sonko.❤️

Mexican Oregano + Oyster leaf

During our Mexico pop-up in 2017, a local forager introduced the test kitchen to Mexican oregano, which blew their mind with its spicy, aromatic flavor and juicy texture. It’s an ingredient we revisit often for this very reason.

Currently on our summer menu, we brush the mexican oregano leaf with oyster and parsley, and serve alongside an oyster leaf…which really does taste like an oyster! 

We grow both the mexican oregano and oyster leaf plants in-house, and harvest daily just before service.

node.text:
Every summer, around late July/early August, we ferry out to an island in the middle of the Baltic Sea. Often referred to as Solskinsøen, (Sunshine Island), Bornholm is where we harvest mulberries from a very special tree that’s close to 150 years old. 

There’s nothing better than biting into these delicious sun-kissed berries, and for just a few days a year you’ll find them on our menu.

node.text:
Rosehip bushes (Rosa Rugrosa), are very common along the coastlines of Denmark, where they were planted as windbreaks in the 1950s. Native to Japan, the earliest records of its introduction to Europe date back to 1796, and here in Denmark, 1875. 

During the harvest season, which general runs from late May to late July, we’ll process close to 100kg of petals, to be used in a myriad of ways including as oil, pickled roses, miso, kombucha, and spice mixes. It’s as an ingredient we revisit often on our menu– currently as part of the main dish of danish blue lobster, and in the past our grilled rose ice cream (from old noma).
